  <div class="glass-card" style="margin-bottom: 2rem;">
    <h2 style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
      <i class="ri-lightbulb-flash-line" style="color: var(--primary);"></i> The Mission
    </h2>
    <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
      AniLens was built to answer the eternal question: <strong>"What anime is this from?"</strong>
    </p>
    <p style="margin-bottom: 0;">
      Think of it as a <em>PokeDex</em> for <strong>Anime Screenshots</strong>. It uses <em>Shinigami Eyes</em> to scan the image via <strong>trace.moe</strong> and instantly write the name from <strong>AniList</strong>. Stop struggling like an <em>E-Rank Hunter</em> in the comments just to find the anime title.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="warning-box">
    <i class="ri-alert-line warning-icon"></i>
    <div>
      <h4 style="color: #fcd34d; margin-top: 0; font-size: 1.1rem;">Limitations (Binding Vows)</h4>
      <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); font-size: 0.95rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        To ensure the technique works, you must respect the rules:
      </p>
      <ul style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.7); font-size: 0.9rem; padding-left: 1.2rem; margin: 0;">
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
          <strong>Raw Anime Screenshots Only:</strong> The algorithm matches exact frames. It cannot detect <strong>Fan Art</strong>, <strong>Doujinshi</strong>, or <strong>Memes</strong> (the system cannot see through <em>Genjutsu</em>).
        </li>
        <li style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
          <strong>No Cropping:</strong> Images must be <strong>uncropped</strong>. A cut-off image is like an incomplete <em>Domain Expansion</em>—the search won't activate properly.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Visual Clarity:</strong> Results depend on distinctiveness. Even <em>Saitama</em> misses a mosquito sometimes (it's not 100% perfect).
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

